03958nam a22004215i 9780804766883DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20042004cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047668837 a10.1515/97808047668832doi  a(DE-B1597)582296  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aDeBernardi, Jean, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRites of Belonging :bMemory, Modernity, and Identity in a Malaysian Chinese Community /cJean DeBernardi. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b26 illustrations, 5 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tMaps and Illustrations -- tPreface -- tA Note on Romanization -- tIntroduction -- tPart One: Religion and Society in Colonial Penang -- t1. The Localization of Chinese Society in Colonial Penang -- t2. ''A Very Irreligious but Most Superstitious People": Trust, Tolerance, and Control in the Straits Settlements, 1786-1857 -- t3. Belonging and Boundaries: European Freemasons and Chinese Sworn Brotherhoods -- t4. Rites of Belonging: Initiation into the Chinese Sworn Brotherhoods -- tPart Two: Religion and the Politics of Ethnic Revival in Contemporary Penang -- t5. Rights of Belonging: Citizenship and Ethnic Nationalism -- t6. Time, Space, and Social Memory -- t7. The Politics of a Religious Revitalization: The Hungry Ghosts Festival -- t8. Performing Magical Power: The Nine Emperor Gods Festival -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: Chinese Festivals Celebrated in Penang, Malaysia -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tGlossary of Chinese Terms -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn what is today Malaysia, the British established George Town on Penang Island in 1786, and encouraged Chinese merchants and laborers to migrate to this vibrant trading port. In the multicultural urban settlement that developed, the Chinese immigrants organized their social life through community temples like the Guanyin Temple (Kong Hok Palace) and their secret sworn brotherhoods. These community associations assumed exceptional importance precisely because they were a means to establish a social presence for the Chinese immigrants, to organize their social life, and to display their economic prowess. The Confucian "cult of memory" also took on new meanings in the early twentieth century as a form of racial pride. In twentieth-century Penang, religious practices and events continued to draw the boundaries of belonging in the idiom of the sacred. Part I of Rites of Belonging focuses on the conjuncture between Chinese and British in colonial Penang. The author closely analyzes the 1857 Guanyin Temple Riots and conflicts leading to the suppression of the Chinese sworn brotherhoods. Part II investigates the conjuncture between Chinese and Malays in contemporary Malaysia, and the revitalization in the 1970s and 1980s of Chinese popular religious culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476688340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804766883423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804766883/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles